webpackJsonp([0x7dbc7a154135],{850:function(e,t){e.exports={data:{post:{id:"/data/projects/work/self/website/content/posts/2018-06-07--generating-entropy-in-linux/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<p>In Linux, sometimes you may need to generate some entropy.</p>\n<h1>Solutions</h1>\n<p>There are both <em>hardware</em> and <em>software</em> solutions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Hardware solutions</strong>: they can <em>generate more entropy per second</em>, but you need physical access</li>\n<li><strong>Software solutions</strong>: they have less performance, but you just need <code class="language-text">root</code> permissions (no physical access)</li>\n</ul>\n<h1>Hardware solutions</h1>\n<p>Typically it’s a USB device that <em>generates and streams some random numbers</em>.</p>\n<p>One of such devices is <a href="http://ubld.it/products/truerng-hardware-random-number-generator">TrueRNG</a> (price is approx: 50$).</p>\n<h1>Software solutions</h1>\n<h2>RNGD</h2>\n<p>This program feeds random data from hardware device to kernel.</p>\n<div class="gatsby-highlight">\n      <pre class="language-text"><code class="language-text">rngd -r &quot;/dev/urandom&quot;</code></pre>\n      </div>\n<p>Here we have used <code class="language-text">rngd</code> program (<a href="http://linux.die.net/man/8/rngd">man 8 rngd</a> for more details).</p>\n<p>This daemon feeds data from a random number generator to the kernel’s random number entropy pool, after first checking the data to ensure that it is properly random.</p>\n<h2>Audio Entropy Daemon</h2>\n<p>This program feeds the <code class="language-text">/dev/random</code> device with entropy-data read from an audio device.</p>\n<p>The audio-data is not copied as is but first <em>de-biased</em> and analysed to determine how much bits of entropy is in it.</p>\n<p>The official website of the program is <a href="https://www.vanheusden.com/aed">here</a>.</p>',fields:{slug:"/generating-entropy-in-linux/",prefix:"2018-06-07"},frontmatter:{title:"Generating Entropy in Linux",subTitle:"A walkthrough on the available solutions for feeding the kernel with some entropy",category:"Linux",status:"Done",revision:1,confidence:"Almost Certain",importance:5,cover:{childImageSharp:{resize:{src:"/static/entropy-cover-6be686e4ac6c77555b5f598ad154cbe8-ada8c.jpg"}}}}},author:{id:"/data/projects/work/self/website/content/parts/author.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:"<p><strong>Alessandro Molari</strong>   Cyber-Security Consultant &#x26; Ethical Hacker, specialized in Red Teaming, Penetration Testing, Advanced Persistent Threat (APT), Vulnerability Research &#x26; Malware Analysis</p>"},footnote:{id:"/data/projects/work/self/website/content/parts/footnote.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:'<ul>\n<li>website prodly built by <a href="https://alessandro.molari.me">Alessandro Molari</a></li>\n<li>using the awesome triad\n<a href="https://gentoo.org"><img src="/icons/gentoo.svg" alt="Gentoo"></a> &#x26;\n<a href="https://xmonad.org"><img src="/icons/xmonad.svg" alt="XMonad"></a> &#x26;\n<a href="https://www.vim.org"><img src="/icons/vim.svg" alt="Vim"></a></li>\n</ul>'},site:{siteMetadata:{facebook:{appId:""}}}},pathContext:{slug:"/generating-entropy-in-linux/"}}}});
